# **Part 2**

## **Describe one of your friends who learned a skill from someone (not a teacher).**

One of my friends who learned an important skill from someone other than a teacher is one of my university classmates named Kevin. He’s really interested in photography and video editing, and over the past few years he has become surprisingly skilled at it. What’s interesting is that he didn’t learn these skills in school at all.

Instead, he mainly learned from his older cousin, who works as a freelance photographer. During school holidays, Kevin would often spend time with him, watching how he used cameras, adjusted lighting, and edited videos on his computer. At first, Kevin only learned some very basic things, like how to frame photos properly or how to use editing software. But later, he started practicing by himself almost every day. He also watched online tutorials and asked his cousin for advice whenever he encountered difficulties.

Now he’s actually very good at making short videos and taking professional-looking photos. Sometimes he even helps student clubs create promotional videos for campus events. I think what impressed me most is that he learned everything through real practice instead of formal classroom lessons.

Personally, I think learning from experienced people can sometimes be even more effective than learning from teachers, especially for practical skills. Teachers usually provide systematic knowledge, which is important, but learning from someone with real-life experience often feels more natural and flexible. For example, Kevin’s cousin taught him many practical tips that probably wouldn’t appear in textbooks. However, I still think teachers are necessary because they help learners build a solid foundation and avoid developing bad habits.

Overall, Kevin’s experience made me realize that learning doesn’t only happen in schools. Nowadays, people can gain valuable skills from friends, family members, or even online communities as long as they’re motivated enough.

---

## **中文翻译：**

我有一个朋友叫 Kevin，是我的大学同学。他对摄影和视频剪辑特别感兴趣，这几年已经变得非常厉害了。有趣的是，他这些技能并不是在学校里学的。

相反，他主要是向自己的表哥学习的。他表哥是一名自由摄影师。每到假期，Kevin 都会和他待在一起，看他如何使用相机、调整灯光以及在电脑上剪辑视频。刚开始的时候，他只是学一些基础内容，比如如何构图、如何使用剪辑软件。但后来他几乎每天都会自己练习。如果遇到问题，他还会去问表哥，同时也会看很多线上教程。

现在他已经非常擅长拍照和制作短视频了。有时候他甚至会帮学校社团制作宣传视频。我最佩服的一点是，他几乎完全通过实践学会了这些技能，而不是依靠正式课堂。

我个人认为，向有经验的人学习有时候甚至比向老师学习更有效，尤其是在实践技能方面。老师通常会提供系统性的知识，这当然很重要；但有真实经验的人教出来的东西往往更自然、更灵活。比如 Kevin 的表哥教了他很多实际技巧，而这些内容课本里可能根本学不到。不过我依然觉得老师很重要，因为他们能够帮助学习者建立扎实基础，并避免形成错误习惯。

总的来说，Kevin 的经历让我意识到，学习不仅仅发生在学校里。如今，只要有足够的动力，人们其实可以从朋友、家人甚至网络社区中学到很多有价值的技能。

